# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hvac-building-automation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] BACnet was designed to allow communication of building automation and control systems for applications such as heating, ventilating, and air-conditioning control (HVAC), lighting control, access control, and fire detection systems and their associated equipment.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The BACnet protocol provides mechanisms for computerized building automation devices to exchange information, regardless of the particular building service they perform.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The development of the BACnet protocol began in June, 1987, in Nashville, Tennessee, at the inaugural meeting of the ASHRAE BACnet committee, known at that time as SPC 135P, "EMCS Message Protocol".
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The committee worked at reaching consensus using working groups to divide up the task of creating a standard.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The working groups focused on specific areas and provided information and recommendations to the main committee.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The first three working groups were the Data Type and Attribute Working Group, Primitive Data Format Working Group, and the Application Services Working Group.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] BACnet became ANSI/ASHRAE Standard 135 in 1995.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] BACnet had an almost immediate impact on the HVAC controls industry.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] In 1996 Alerton announced a BACnet product line for HVAC controls, from the operator's workstation to small variable air volume (VAV) controllers.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Automated Logic Corporation and Delta Controls soon followed suit.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The Method of Test for Conformance to BACnet was published in 2003 as BSR/ASHRAE Standard 135.1.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] BACnet became an international (ISO) standard as ISO 16484-5:2003.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The Method of Test would soon follow as ISO 16484-6:2005.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] BACnet is under continuous maintenance by the ASHRAE Standing Standard Project Committee 135.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] On July 12, 2017, BACnet reached a milestone with the issuance of the 1000th Vendor ID.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Vendor IDs are assigned by ASHRAE and are distributed internationally.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Those vendor identifiers can be viewed at the BACnet website Archived 2009-11-21 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Michael (Mike) Newman, Manager of the Computer Section of the Utilities and Energy Management Department at Cornell University, served as the BACnet committee chairman until June, 2000, when he was succeeded by his vice-chair of 13 years, Steven (Steve) Bushby from NIST.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] 2000–The BACnet Manufacturers’ Association (BMA) is formed and soon opens the BACnet Testing Laboratory.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The first president of BMA is James Lee.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] BACnet is translated into Chinese and Japanese.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] BMA sponsors first BACnet Interoperability Workshop (“PlugFest”) at NIST with 12 organizations attending.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] (PlugFest-2012 had 49 teams.) BACnet Testing Laboratories (BTL) was formed and James Butler was a founding manager of BTL.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] During Steve Bushby's four-year term as committee chair the BACnet standard was republished twice, in 2001 and 2004, each time with new capabilities added to the standard.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The 2001 version featured, among other things, extensions to support fire / life-safety systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] In June, 2004, 17 years after the first BACnet meeting and back in Nashville, William (Bill) Swan (a.k.a.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] "BACnet Bill") from Alerton began his four-year stint as committee chair.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] During his term the number of committee working groups grew to 11, pursuing areas such as support for lighting, access control, energy utility/building integration, and wireless communications.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] In January 2006 the BACnet Manufacturers Association and the BACnet Interest Group of North America combined their operation in a new organization called BACnet International Archived 2020-08-17 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] In June 2008, in Salt Lake City, Dave Robin from Automated Logic Corporation took over the reins as the new committee chair after serving 4 years as vice chair.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] During Dave's term, 22 addenda were published for the 135-2008 standard and republished as 135-2010.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Several addenda were published for 135-2010 and the standard was republished as 135-2012.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] In June 2012, in San Antonio, Carl Neilson from Delta Controls took over the reins as the new committee chair after serving 4 years as vice chair.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] During Carl's term, 12 addenda were published for the 135-2012 standard and it was republished as 135-2016.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Carl stepped down as chair in June 2015.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] In June 2015, Bernhard Isler, from Siemens, became chair after serving 3 years as vice chair and 4 years as secretary.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] During Bernhard's term, 10 addenda were published for the 135-2016 standard.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] One addendum to 135.1-2013 was also published.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Bernhard stepped down as chair in June 2018.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] In June 2018, Michael Osborne from Reliable Controls, became chair after serving 3 years as secretary and 3 years as vice chair.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The BACnet protocol defines a number of services that are used to communicate between building devices.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The protocol services include Who-Is, I-Am, Who-Has, I-Have, which are used for Device and Object discovery.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Services such as Read-Property and Write-Property are used for data sharing.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] As of ANSI/ASHRAE 135-2016, the BACnet protocol defines 60 object types that are acted upon by the services.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The BACnet protocol defines a number of data link and physical layers, including ARCNET, Ethernet, BACnet/IP, BACnet/IPv6, BACnet/MSTP, point-to-point over RS-232, multidrop serial bus with token passing over RS-485, Zigbee, and LonTalk.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] BACnet Testing Laboratories ("BTL") was established by BACnet International to test products to BACnet standards and support compliance testing and interoperability testing activities and consists of BTL Manager and the BTL working group ("BTL-WG").
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The BTL also provides testing services through BACnet Laboratories.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] The BTL Managers and BTL working groups of BACnet International administer the test Laboratories.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] All BTL-recognized BACnet Test Organizations are ISO 17025 accredited.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] In January, 2017, a new BTL certification program was announced.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] Under this program, the work of the BTL and WSPCert (the European BACnet certification body) is merged.
[src:hvac-building-automation/bacnet] This merger forms a single point of testing for both the BTL Mark and the Certificate of Conformance.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] BAS functionality may keep a building's climate within a specified range, provide light to rooms based on occupancy, monitor performance and device failures, and provide malfunction alarms to building maintenance staff.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] A BAS works to reduce building energy and maintenance costs compared to a non-controlled building.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Most commercial, institutional, and industrial buildings built after 2000 include a BAS, whilst older buildings may be retrofitted with a new BAS.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] A building controlled by a BAS is often referred to as an "intelligent building", a "smart building", or (if a residence) a *smart home*.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Commercial and industrial buildings have historically relied on robust proven protocols (like BACnet) while proprietary protocols (like X-10) were used in homes.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] With the advent of wireless sensor networks and the Internet of Things, an increasing number of smart buildings are resorting to using low-power wireless communication technologies such as Zigbee, Bluetooth Low Energy and LoRa to interconnect the local sensors, actuators and processing devices.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Almost all multi-story green buildings are designed to accommodate a BAS for the energy, air and water conservation characteristics.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Electrical device demand response is a typical function of a BAS, as is the more sophisticated ventilation and humidity monitoring required of "tight" insulated buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Most green buildings also use as many low-power DC devices as possible.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Even a passivhaus design intended to consume no net energy whatsoever will typically require a BAS to manage heat capture, shading and venting, and scheduling device use.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Building management systems are most commonly implemented in large projects with extensive mechanical, HVAC, and electrical systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Systems linked to a BMS typically represent 40% of a building's energy usage; if lighting is included, this number approaches to 70%.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] BMS systems are a critical component to managing energy demand.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Improperly configured BMS systems are believed to account for 20% of building energy usage, or approximately 8% of total energy usage in the United States.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] In addition to controlling the building's internal environment, BMS systems are sometimes linked to access control (turnstiles and access doors controlling who is allowed access and egress to the building) or other security systems such as closed-circuit television (CCTV) and motion detectors.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Fire alarm systems and elevators are also sometimes linked to a BMS for monitoring.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] In case a fire is detected then only the fire alarm panel could close dampers in the ventilation system to stop smoke spreading, shut down air handlers, start smoke evacuation fans, and send all the elevators to the ground floor and park them to prevent people from using them.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Building management systems have also included disaster-response mechanisms (such as base isolation) to save structures from earthquakes.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] In more recent times, companies and governments have been working to find similar solutions for flood zones and coastal areas at-risk to rising sea levels.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Self-adjusting floating environment draws from existing technologies used to float concrete bridges and runways such as Washington's SR 520 and Japan's Mega-Float.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Analog inputs are used to read a variable measurement.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Examples are temperature, humidity and pressure sensors which could be thermistor, 4–20 mA, 0–10 volt or platinum resistance thermometer (resistance temperature detector), or wireless sensors.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] A digital input indicates a device is on or off.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Some examples of digital inputs would be a door contact switch, a current switch, an air flow switch, or a voltage-free relay contact (dry contact).
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Digital inputs could also be pulse inputs counting the pulses over a period of time.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] An example is a turbine flow meter transmitting flow data as a frequency of pulses to an input.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Nonintrusive load monitoring is software relying on digital sensors and algorithms to discover appliance or other loads from electrical or magnetic characteristics of the circuit.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] It is however detecting the event by an analog means.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] These are extremely cost-effective in operation and useful not only for identification but to detect start-up transients, line or equipment faults, etc.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Occupancy sensors detect the presence, number, and sometimes location of people in a space to enable demand-controlled systems for lighting, HVAC, and energy management.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Traditional examples include passive infrared (PIR), ultrasonic, and CO2-based detectors, but advanced systems use low-resolution thermal imaging or area sensors to provide zone-level accuracy without capturing identifiable images, ensuring privacy compliance (e.g., GDPR).
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] These sensors output analog heat signatures or digital counts that integrate with building management systems via protocols like BACnet or wireless IoT networks, reducing energy use by up to 40% through precise ventilation and lighting control.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Analog outputs control the speed or position of a device, such as a variable frequency drive, an I-P (current to pneumatics) transducer, or a valve or damper actuator.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] An example is a hot water valve opening up 25% to maintain a setpoint.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Another example is a variable frequency drive ramping up a motor slowly to avoid a hard start.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Digital outputs are used to open and close relays and switches as well as drive a load upon command.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] An example would be to turn on the parking lot lights when a photocell indicates it is dark outside.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Another example would be to open a valve by allowing 24VDC/AC to pass through the output powering the valve.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Analog outputs could also be pulse type outputs emitting a frequency of pulses over a given period of time.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] An example is an energy meter calculating kWh and emitting a frequency of pulses accordingly.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Controllers are essentially small, purpose-built computers with input and output capabilities.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] These controllers come in a range of sizes and capabilities to control devices commonly found in buildings, and to control sub-networks of controllers.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Inputs allow a controller to read temperature, humidity, pressure, current flow, air flow, and other essential factors.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] The outputs allow the controller to send command and control signals to slave devices, and to other parts of the system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Inputs and outputs can be either digital or analog.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Digital outputs are also sometimes called discrete depending on manufacturer.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Controllers used for building automation can be grouped in three categories: programmable logic controllers (PLCs), system/network controllers, and terminal unit controllers.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] However an additional device can also exist in order to integrate third-party systems (e.g. a stand-alone AC system) into a central building automation system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Terminal unit controllers usually are suited for control of lighting and/or simpler devices such as a package rooftop unit, heat pump, VAV box, fan coil, etc.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] The installer typically selects one of the available pre-programmed personalities best suited to the device to be controlled, and does not have to create new control logic.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Occupancy is one of two or more operating modes for a building automation system; unoccupied, morning warmup, and night-time setback are other common modes.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Occupancy is usually based on time of day schedules.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] In occupancy mode, the BAS aims to provides a comfortable climate and adequate lighting, often with zone-based control so that users on one side of a building have a different thermostat (or a different system, or sub system) than users on the opposite side.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] A temperature sensor in the zone provides feedback to the controller, so it can deliver heating or cooling as needed.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] If enabled, morning warmup (MWU) mode occurs prior to occupancy.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] During morning warmup the BAS tries to bring the building to setpoint just in time for occupancy.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] The BAS often factors in outdoor conditions and historical experience to optimize MWU.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] This is also referred to as *optimized start*.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Some buildings rely on occupancy sensors to activate lighting or climate conditioning.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Given the potential for long lead times before a space becomes sufficiently cool or warm, climate conditioning is not often initiated directly by an occupancy sensor.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Lighting can be turned on, off, or dimmed with a building automation or lighting control system based on time of day, or on occupancy sensor, photosensors and timers.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] One typical example is to turn the lights in a space on for a half-hour since the last motion was sensed.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] A photocell placed outside a building can sense darkness, and the time of day, and modulate lights in outer offices and the parking lot.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Lighting is also a good candidate for demand response, with many control systems providing the ability to dim (or turn off) lights to take advantage of DR incentives and savings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] In newer buildings, the lighting control can be based on the field bus Digital Addressable Lighting Interface (DALI).
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Lamps with DALI ballasts are fully dimmable.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] DALI can also detect lamp and ballast failures on DALI luminaires and signals failures.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Shading and glazing are essential components in the building system, they affect occupants' visual, acoustical, and thermal comfort and provide the occupant with a view outdoor.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Automated shading and glazing systems are solutions for controlling solar heat gains and glare.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] It refers to the use of technology to control external or internal shading devices (such as blinds, and shades) or glazing itself.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] The system has an active and rapid response to various changing outdoor data (such as solar, wind) and to changing interior environment (such as temperature, illuminance, and occupant demands).
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Building shading and glazing systems can contribute to thermal and lighting improvement from both energy conservation and comfort point of view.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Dynamic shading devices allow the control of daylight and solar energy to enter into built environment in relation to outdoor conditions, daylighting demands and solar positions.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] The common products include venetian blinds, roller shades, louvers, and shutters.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] They are mostly installed on the interior side of the glazing system because of the low maintenance cost, but also can be used on the exterior or a combination of both.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Most air handlers mix return and outside air so less temperature/humidity conditioning is needed.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] This can save money by using less chilled or heated water (not all AHUs use chilled or hot water circuits).
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Some external air is needed to keep the building's air healthy.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] To optimize energy efficiency while maintaining healthy indoor air quality (IAQ), demand control (or controlled) ventilation (DCV) adjusts the amount of outside air based on measured levels of occupancy.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Analog or digital temperature sensors may be placed in the space or room, the return and supply air ducts, and sometimes the external air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Actuators are placed on the hot and chilled water valves, the outside air and return air dampers.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] The supply fan (and return if applicable) is started and stopped based on either time of day, temperatures, building pressures or a combination.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] All modern building automation systems have alarm capabilities.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] It does little good to detect a potentially hazardous or costly situation if no one who can solve the problem is notified.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Notification can be through a computer (email or text message), pager, cellular phone voice call, audible alarm, or all of these.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] For insurance and liability purposes all systems keep logs of who was notified, when and how.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Alarms may immediately notify someone or only notify when alarms build to some threshold of seriousness or urgency.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] At sites with several buildings, momentary power failures can cause hundreds or thousands of alarms from equipment that has shut down – these should be suppressed and recognized as symptoms of a larger failure.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Some sites are programmed so that critical alarms are automatically re-sent at varying intervals.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] For example, a repeating critical alarm (of an uninterruptible power supply in 'bypass') might resound at 10 minutes, 30 minutes, and every 2 to 4 hours thereafter until the alarms are resolved.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Security systems can be interlocked to a building automation system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] If occupancy sensors are present, they can also be used as burglar alarms.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Because security systems are often deliberately sabotaged, at least some detectors or cameras should have battery backup and wireless connectivity and the ability to trigger alarms when disconnected.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Modern systems typically use power-over-Ethernet (which can operate a pan-tilt-zoom camera and other devices up to 30–90 watts) which is capable of charging such batteries and keeps wireless networks free for genuinely wireless applications, such as backup communication in outage.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Fire alarm panels and their related smoke alarm systems are usually hard-wired to override building automation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] For example: if the smoke alarm is activated, all the outside air dampers close to prevent air coming into the building, and an exhaust system can isolate the blaze.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Similarly, electrical fault detection systems can turn entire circuits off, regardless of the number of alarms this triggers or persons this distresses.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Fossil fuel combustion devices also tend to have their own over-rides, such as natural gas feed lines that turn off when slow pressure drops are detected (indicating a leak), or when excess methane is detected in the building's air supply.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] ASHRAE's open protocol BACnet or the open protocol LonTalk specify how most such devices interoperate.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Modern systems use SNMP to track events, building on decades of history with SNMP-based protocols in the computer networking world.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Physical connectivity between devices was historically provided by dedicated optical fiber, ethernet, ARCNET, RS-232, RS-485 or a low-bandwidth special purpose wireless network.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Modern systems rely on standards-based multi-protocol heterogeneous networking such as that specified in the IEEE 1905.1 standard and verified by the nVoy auditing mark.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Proprietary hardware dominates the controller market.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Each company has controllers for specific applications.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Some are designed with limited controls and no interoperability, such as simple packaged roof top units for HVAC.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Software will typically not integrate well with packages from other vendors.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Cooperation is at the Zigbee/BACnet/LonTalk level only.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Current systems provide interoperability at the application level, allowing users to mix-and-match devices from different manufacturers, and to provide integration with other compatible building control systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] These typically rely on SNMP, long used for this same purpose to integrate diverse computer networking devices into one coherent network.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] With the growing spectrum of capabilities and connections to the Internet of Things, building automation systems were repeatedly reported to be vulnerable, allowing hackers and cybercriminals to attack their components.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Buildings can be exploited by hackers to measure or change their environment: sensors allow surveillance (e.g. monitoring movements of employees or habits of inhabitants) while actuators allow to perform actions in buildings (e.g. opening doors or windows for intruders).
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] Several vendors and committees started to improve the security features in their products and standards, including KNX, Zigbee and BACnet (see recent standards or standard drafts).
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] However, researchers report several open problems in building automation security.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] On November 11, 2019, a 132-page security research paper was released titled "I Own Your Building (Management System)" by Gjoko Krstic and Sipke Mellema that addressed more than 100 vulnerabilities affecting various BMS and access control solutions by various vendors.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] On November 24, 2025, a 161-page security research paper was released titled "Project Brainfog: Beyond the Facade - Exposing Smart Giants" by Gjoko Krstic that addressed more than 1000 vulnerabilities affecting two widely used BAS controllers by ABB Group.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] It is common for room automation systems to employ a touchscreen as the primary way of controlling each operation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] On November 27, 2018, a 29-page research paper titled "A Scalable Room Occupancy Prediction with Transferable Time Series Decomposition of CO2 Sensor Data" was published by Irvan Bastian Arief, Margaret Hamilton, and Flora Salim.
[src:hvac-building-automation/building-automation] The paper introduced a novel approach to leveraging carbon dioxide (CO2) sensor data to predict room occupancy—enabling smarter building automation by estimating the number of occupants in a room at any given time.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The three major functions of heating, ventilation, and air conditioning are intertwined.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] HVAC systems can provide ventilation and maintain pressure relationships between spaces.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The means of air delivery and removal from spaces is known as room air distribution.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In modern buildings, the design, installation, and control systems of these functions are integrated into one or more HVAC systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For very small buildings, contractors normally estimate the capacity and type of system needed and then design the system, selecting the appropriate refrigerant and various components needed.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For larger buildings, building service designers, mechanical engineers, or building services engineers analyze, design, and specify the HVAC systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Specialty mechanical contractors and suppliers then fabricate, install, and commission the systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Building permits and code-compliance inspections of the installations are normally required for all sizes of buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Although HVAC is executed in individual buildings or other enclosed spaces (like NORAD's underground headquarters), the equipment involved is in some cases an extension of a larger district heating (DH) or district cooling (DC) network, or a combined DHC (District-Heating-Cooling) network.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In such cases, the operating and maintenance aspects are simplified, and metering becomes necessary to bill for the energy that is consumed and, in some cases, energy that is returned to the larger system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For example, at a given time, one building may be utilizing chilled water for air conditioning, and the warm water it returns may be used in another building for heating or for the overall heating-portion of the DHC network (likely with energy added to boost the temperature).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] HVAC is based on inventions and discoveries made by Nikolay Lvov, Michael Faraday, Rolla C.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Carpenter, Willis Carrier, Edwin Ruud, Reuben Trane, James Joule, William Rankine, Sadi Carnot, Alice Parker and many others.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Coyne College was the first school to offer HVAC training in 1899.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The first residential AC was installed by 1914, and by the 1950s there was "widespread adoption of residential AC".
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Heating is the process of transferring thermal energy to an enclosed space in order to raise or maintain its temperature for the comfort of its occupants.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In central heating systems, a central source such as a boiler, furnace, or heat pump supplies thermal energy at a central location, and air, water, or steam transfers that energy to the spaces to be heated, where it is delivered by convection, radiation, or both.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Small space heaters may also be used to heat individual rooms.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Heaters exist for various types of fuel, including solid fuels, liquids, and gases.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Another type of heat source is electricity, normally heating ribbons composed of high resistance wire (see Nichrome).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] This principle is also used for baseboard heaters and portable heaters.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Electrical heaters are often used as backup or supplemental heat for heat pump systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The heat pump gained popularity in the 1950s in Japan and the United States.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Heat pumps can extract heat from various sources, such as environmental air, exhaust air from a building, or from the ground.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Heat pumps transfer heat from outside the structure to the air inside.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Initially, heat pump HVAC systems were only used in moderate climates, but with improvements in low temperature operation and reduced loads due to more efficient homes, they are increasing in popularity in cooler climates.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] They can also operate in reverse to cool an interior.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In the case of heated water or steam, piping is used to transport the heat to the rooms.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Most modern hot water boiler heating systems have a circulator, which is a pump, to move hot water through the distribution system (as opposed to older gravity-fed systems).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The heat can be transferred to the surrounding air using radiators, hot water coils (hydro-air), or other heat exchangers.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The radiators may be mounted on walls or installed within the floor to produce floor heat.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The use of water as the heat transfer medium is known as hydronics.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The heated water can also supply an auxiliary heat exchanger to supply hot water for bathing and washing.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Warm air systems distribute the heated air through ductwork systems of supply and return air through metal or fiberglass ducts.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Many systems use the same ducts to distribute air cooled by an evaporator coil for air conditioning.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The air supply is normally filtered through air filters to remove dust and pollen particles.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The use of furnaces, space heaters, and boilers as a method of indoor heating can result in incomplete combustion and the emission of carbon monoxide, nitrogen oxides, formaldehyde, volatile organic compounds, and other combustion byproducts.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Incomplete combustion occurs when there is insufficient oxygen; the inputs are fuels containing various contaminants and the outputs are harmful byproducts, such as carbon monoxide, a tasteless and odorless gas with serious adverse health effects.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Ventilation is the process of changing or replacing air in any space to control the temperature or remove any combination of moisture, odors, smoke, heat, dust, airborne bacteria, or carbon dioxide, and to replenish oxygen.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Different methods, such as natural ventilation through windows and mechanical ventilation systems, can be used depending on the building design and air quality needs.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Ventilation often refers to the intentional delivery of outside air to an indoor space to maintain acceptable air quality in buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The effectiveness of ventilation depends on both indoor and outdoor air quality conditions, as well as on factors such as health impacts and energy demand.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Where outdoor air pollution would degrade indoor air quality, additional treatment measures, such as air filtration, may be necessary.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Methods for ventilating a building may be divided into *mechanical/forced* and *natural* types.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Mechanical, or forced, ventilation is provided by an air handler (AHU) and used to control indoor air quality.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Excess humidity, odors, and contaminants can often be controlled via dilution or replacement with outside air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] However, in humid climates more energy is required to remove excess moisture from ventilation air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Kitchens and bathrooms typically have mechanical exhausts to control odors and sometimes humidity.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Factors in the design of such systems include the flow rate (which is a function of the fan speed and exhaust vent size) and noise level.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Direct drive fans are available for many applications and can reduce maintenance needs.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In summer, ceiling fans and table/floor fans circulate air within a room for the purpose of reducing the perceived temperature by increasing evaporation of perspiration on the skin of the occupants.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Because hot air rises, ceiling fans may be used to keep a room warmer in the winter by circulating the warm stratified air from the ceiling to the floor.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Natural ventilation is the ventilation of a building with outside air without using fans or other mechanical systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] It can be via operable windows, louvers, or trickle vents when spaces are small and the architecture permits.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] ASHRAE defined Natural ventilation as the flow of air through open windows, doors, grilles, and other planned building envelope penetrations, and as being driven by natural and/or artificially produced pressure differentials.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Natural ventilation strategies also include cross ventilation, which relies on wind pressure differences on opposite sides of a building.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] By strategically placing openings, such as windows or vents, on opposing walls, air is channeled through the space to enhance cooling and ventilation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Cross ventilation is most effective when there are clear, unobstructed paths for airflow within the building.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In more complex schemes, warm air is allowed to rise and flow out high building openings to the outside (stack effect), causing cool outside air to be drawn into low building openings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Natural ventilation schemes typically use very little energy, but are sensitive to environmental factors.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In warm or humid climates, maintaining thermal comfort solely via natural ventilation might not be possible.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Air conditioning systems are used, either as backups or supplements.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Air-side economizers also use outside air to condition spaces, but do so using fans, ducts, dampers, and control systems to introduce and distribute cool outdoor air when appropriate.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] A component of natural ventilation is air change rate or air changes per hour: the hourly rate of ventilation divided by the volume of the space.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For example, six air changes per hour means an amount of new air, equal to the volume of the space, is added every ten minutes.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For human comfort, a minimum of four air changes per hour is typical, though warehouses might have only two.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Too high of an air change rate may be uncomfortable, akin to a wind tunnel which has thousands of changes per hour.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The highest air change rates are for crowded spaces, bars, night clubs, commercial kitchens at around 30 to 50 air changes per hour.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Room pressure can be either positive or negative with respect to outside the room.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Positive pressure occurs when there is more air being supplied than exhausted, and is common to reduce the infiltration of outside contaminants.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Natural ventilation is a factor in reducing the spread of airborne illnesses such as tuberculosis, the common cold, influenza, meningitis or COVID-19.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Opening doors and windows are ways to maximize natural ventilation, making the risk of airborne contagion much lower.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Natural ventilation requires little maintenance and is inexpensive.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Ventilation is measured in terms of Air Changes Per Hour (ACH).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] As of 2023, the CDC recommends that all spaces have a minimum of 5 ACH.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For hospital rooms with airborne contagions the CDC recommends a minimum of 12 ACH.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The challenges in facility ventilation are public unawareness, ineffective government oversight, poor building codes that are based on comfort levels, poor system operations, poor maintenance, and lack of transparency.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] UVC or Ultraviolet Germicidal Irradiation is a function used in modern air conditioners which reduces airborne viruses, bacteria, and fungi, through the use of LED UV light that emits across the evaporator.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Air is guided through the sterilization module’s irradiation range, rendering viruses inactive.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] An air conditioning system, or a standalone air conditioner, provides cooling and/or humidity control for all or part of a building.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Air conditioned buildings often have sealed windows, because open windows would work against the system intended to maintain constant indoor air conditions.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Outside, fresh air is generally drawn into the system by a vent into a mix air chamber for mixing with the space return air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Then the mixture air enters an indoor or outdoor heat exchanger section where the air is to be cooled down, then be guided to the space creating positive air pressure.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The percentage of return air made up of fresh air can usually be manipulated by adjusting the opening of this vent.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Typical fresh air intake is about 10% of the total supply air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Air conditioning and refrigeration are provided through the removal of heat.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Heat can be removed through radiation, convection, or conduction.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The heat transfer medium is a refrigeration system, such as water, air, ice, and chemicals are referred to as refrigerants.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] A refrigerant is employed either in a heat pump system in which a compressor is used to drive thermodynamic refrigeration cycle, or in a free cooling system that uses pumps to circulate a cool refrigerant (typically water or a glycol mix).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The refrigeration cycle uses four essential elements to cool, which are the compressor, condenser, metering device, and evaporator.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In variable climates, the system may include a reversing valve that switches from heating in winter to cooling in summer.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] By reversing the flow of refrigerant, the heat pump refrigeration cycle is changed from cooling to heating or vice versa.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] This allows a facility to be heated and cooled by a single piece of equipment by the same means, and with the same hardware.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Free cooling systems can have very high efficiencies, and are sometimes combined with seasonal thermal energy storage so that the cold of winter can be used for summer air conditioning.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Common storage mediums include deep aquifers or natural underground rock masses accessed through a cluster of small-diameter boreholes equipped with heat exchangers.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Some systems with small storage capacities are hybrids; they utilize free cooling early in the cooling season and later employ a heat pump to chill the circulation coming from the storage.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The heat pump is added-in because the storage acts as a heat sink when the system is in cooling (as opposed to charging) mode, causing the temperature to gradually increase during the cooling season.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Some systems include an "economizer mode", which is sometimes called a "free-cooling mode".
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] When economizing, the control system will open (fully or partially) the outside air damper and close (fully or partially) the return air damper.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] This will cause fresh, outside air to be supplied to the system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] When the outside air is cooler than the demanded cool air, this will allow the demand to be met without using the mechanical supply of cooling (typically chilled water or a direct expansion "DX" unit), thus saving energy.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The control system can compare the temperature of the outside air vs. return air, or it can compare the enthalpy of the air, as is frequently done in climates where humidity is more of an issue.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In both cases, the outside air must be less energetic than the return air for the system to enter the economizer mode.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Outside of North America, packaged systems are only used in limited applications involving large indoor space such as stadiums, theatres or exhibition halls.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] An alternative to packaged systems is the use of separate indoor and outdoor coils in split systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Split systems are preferred and widely used worldwide except in North America.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In North America, split systems are most often seen in residential applications, but they are gaining popularity in small commercial buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Split systems are used where ductwork is not feasible or where the space conditioning efficiency is of prime concern.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The benefits of ductless air conditioning systems include easy installation, no ductwork, and greater zonal control.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In space conditioning, the duct losses can account for 30% of energy consumption.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The use of minisplits can result in energy savings in space conditioning as there are no losses associated with ducting.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] With the split system, the evaporator coil is connected to a remote condenser unit using refrigerant piping between an indoor and outdoor unit instead of ducting air directly from the outdoor unit.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Indoor units with directional vents mount onto walls, suspended from ceilings, or fit into the ceiling.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Other indoor units mount inside the ceiling cavity so that short lengths of duct handle air from the indoor unit to vents or diffusers around the rooms.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Split systems are more efficient and the footprint is typically smaller than the package systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] On the other hand, package systems tend to have a slightly lower indoor noise level compared to split systems since the fan motor is located outside.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Dehumidification (air drying) in an air conditioning system is provided by the evaporator.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Since the evaporator operates at a temperature below the dew point, moisture in the air condenses on the evaporator coil tubes.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] This moisture is collected at the bottom of the evaporator in a pan and removed by piping to a central drain or onto the ground outside.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] A dehumidifier is an air-conditioner-like device that controls the humidity of a room or building.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] It is often employed in basements that have a higher relative humidity because of their lower temperature (and propensity for damp floors and walls).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In food retailing establishments, large open chiller cabinets are highly effective at dehumidifying the internal air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Conversely, a humidifier increases the humidity of a building.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The HVAC components that dehumidify the ventilation air deserve careful attention because outdoor air constitutes most of the annual humidity load for nearly all buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] A humidifier is a household appliance or device designed to increase the moisture level in the air within a room or an enclosed space.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] It achieves this by emitting water droplets or steam into the surrounding air, thereby raising the humidity.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In the home, point-of-use humidifiers are commonly used to humidify a single room, while whole-house or furnace humidifiers, which connect to a home's HVAC system, provide humidity to the entire house.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Medical ventilators often include humidifiers for increased patient comfort.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Large humidifiers are used in commercial, institutional, or industrial contexts, often as part of a larger HVAC system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Nearly every modern air conditioning system, even small window package units, is equipped with an internal air filter or electrostatic precipitator.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The filters may range from a lightweight gauze-like material to a heavier-duty pleated mat composed of borosilicate glass fibers.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Filters are typically replaced or washed as conditions warrant.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For example, a building in a dusty environment or a home with furry pets will need to have the filters changed more often than interior spaces without these dirt loads.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Failure to replace these filters as needed can contribute to a lower heat exchange rate, resulting in wasted energy, shortened equipment life, and higher energy bills.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Low airflow can result in iced-over evaporator coils, which can completely stop airflow.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Additionally, very dirty or plugged filters can cause overheating during a heating cycle, which can result in damage to the system or even fire.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Because an air conditioner moves heat between the indoor coil and the outdoor coil, both must be kept clean.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] This means that, in addition to replacing the air filter at the evaporator coil, it is also necessary to regularly clean the condenser coil.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Failure to keep the condenser clean will eventually result in harm to the compressor because the condenser coil is responsible for discharging both the indoor heat (as picked up by the evaporator) and the heat generated by the electric motor driving the compressor.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] HVAC systems play a key role in improving the energy efficiency of buildings, as the building sector accounts for one of the highest shares of global energy consumption.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Since the 1980s, HVAC equipment manufacturers have focused on improving system efficiency.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Initially, these efforts were driven by rising energy costs, but in recent years, environmental sustainability and stricter efficiency regulations have become the primary motivators.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Additionally, improving HVAC system efficiency can enhance indoor air quality, which may lead to better occupant health, comfort, and productivity.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In the US, the EPA has imposed tighter restrictions over the years.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] There are several methods for making HVAC systems more efficient.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In the past, water heating was more efficient for heating buildings and was the standard in the United States.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Today, forced air systems can double for air conditioning and are more popular.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Energy efficiency can be improved in central heating systems by using zoned heating.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] This allows a more granular application of heat, similar to non-central heating systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Zones are controlled by multiple thermostats.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In water heating systems the thermostats control zone valves, and in forced air systems they control zone dampers inside the vents which selectively block the flow of air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Forecasting is another method of controlling building heating by calculating the demand for heating energy that should be supplied to the building in each time unit.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Ground source, or geothermal, heat pumps are similar to ordinary heat pumps, but instead of transferring heat to or from outside air, they rely on the stable, even temperature of the earth to provide heating and air conditioning.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Many regions experience seasonal temperature extremes, which would require large-capacity heating and cooling equipment to heat or cool buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] A metre below the earth's surface, however, the ground remains at a relatively constant temperature.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Utilizing this large source of relatively moderate temperature earth, a heating or cooling system's capacity can often be significantly reduced.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Although ground temperatures vary according to latitude, at 1.8 metres (6 ft) underground, temperatures generally only range from 7 to 24 °C (45 to 75 °F).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Photovoltaic solar panels can potentially decrease the operating cost of air conditioning.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Traditional air conditioners run using alternating current, and hence, any direct-current solar power needs to be inverted to be compatible with these units.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] New variable-speed DC-motor units allow solar power to more easily run them since this conversion is unnecessary, and since the motors are tolerant of voltage fluctuations associated with variance in supplied solar power (e.g., due to cloud cover).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Energy recovery systems sometimes utilize heat recovery ventilation or energy recovery ventilation systems that employ heat exchangers or enthalpy wheels to recover sensible or latent heat from exhausted air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] This is done by transfer of energy from the stale air inside the home to the incoming fresh air from outside.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The performance of vapor compression refrigeration cycles is limited by thermodynamics.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] These air conditioning and heat pump devices *move* heat rather than convert it from one form to another, so *thermal efficiencies* do not appropriately describe the performance of these devices.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The Coefficient of performance (COP) measures performance, but this dimensionless measure has not been adopted.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Instead, the Energy Efficiency Ratio (*EER*) has traditionally been used to characterize the performance of many HVAC systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] EER is the Energy Efficiency Ratio based on a 35 °C (95 °F) outdoor temperature.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] To more accurately describe the performance of air conditioning equipment over a typical cooling season a modified version of the EER, the Seasonal Energy Efficiency Ratio (*SEER*), or in Europe the ESEER, is used.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] SEER ratings are based on seasonal temperature averages instead of a constant 35 °C (95 °F) outdoor temperature.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The current industry minimum SEER rating is 14 SEER.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Engineers have pointed out some areas where efficiency of the existing hardware could be improved.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For example, the fan blades used to move the air are usually stamped from sheet metal, an economical method of manufacture, but as a result they are not aerodynamically efficient.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] A well-designed blade could reduce the electrical power required to move the air by a third.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Demand-controlled kitchen ventilation (DCKV) is a building controls approach to controlling the volume of kitchen exhaust and supply air in response to the actual cooking loads in a commercial kitchen.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Traditional commercial kitchen ventilation systems operate at 100% fan speed independent of the volume of cooking activity and DCKV technology changes that to provide significant fan energy and conditioned air savings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] By deploying smart sensing technology, both the exhaust and supply fans can be controlled to capitalize on the affinity laws for motor energy savings, reduce makeup air heating and cooling energy, increasing safety, and reducing ambient kitchen noise levels.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Air cleaning and filtration removes particles, contaminants, vapors and gases from the air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The filtered and cleaned air then is used in heating, ventilation, and air conditioning.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Clean air delivery rate (CADR) is the amount of clean air an air cleaner provides to a room or space.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] When determining CADR, the amount of airflow in a space is taken into account.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For example, an air cleaner with a flow rate of 30 cubic metres (1,000 ft3) per minute and an efficiency of 50% has a CADR of 15 cubic metres (500 ft3) per minute.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Filtration performance determines the fraction of airborne particles, including allergens, bacteria, and fine particulate matter, removed from recirculated air.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] This depends on the size of the particle or fiber, the filter packing density and depth, and the airflow rate.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The HVAC industry includes equipment manufacturing, system design, installation, operation, maintenance, sales, education, and research.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] UL is an omnibus agency and is not specific to the HVAC industry.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] ISO 16813:2006 is one of the ISO building environment standards.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] It establishes the general principles of building environment design.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] It takes into account the need to provide a healthy indoor environment for the occupants as well as the need to protect the environment for future generations and promote collaboration among the various parties involved in building environmental design for sustainability.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] ISO16813 is applicable to new construction and the retrofit of existing buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In the United States, federal licensure is generally handled by EPA certified for installation and service of HVAC devices.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Many U.S. states have licensing for boiler operation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Many HVAC engineers are members of the American Society of Heating, Refrigerating, and Air-Conditioning Engineers (ASHRAE).
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] ASHRAE publishes recognized standards for HVAC design, which are updated every four years.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Another popular society is AHRI, which provides regular information on new refrigeration technology, and publishes relevant standards and codes.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] American design standards are legislated in the Uniform Mechanical Code or International Mechanical Code.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] In certain states, counties, or cities, either of these codes may be adopted and amended via various legislative processes.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] These codes are updated and published by the International Association of Plumbing and Mechanical Officials (IAPMO) or the International Code Council (ICC) respectively, on a 3-year code development cycle.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Typically, local building permit departments are charged with enforcement of these standards on private and certain public properties.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] An **HVAC technician** is a tradesman who specializes in heating, ventilation, air conditioning, and refrigeration.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] HVAC technicians in the US can receive training through formal training institutions, where most earn associate degrees.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Training for HVAC technicians includes classroom lectures and hands-on tasks, and can be followed by an apprenticeship wherein the recent graduate works alongside a professional HVAC technician for a temporary period.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] HVAC techs who have been trained can also be certified in areas such as air conditioning, heat pumps, gas heating, and commercial refrigeration.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The Chartered Institution of Building Services Engineers is a body that covers the essential Service (systems architecture) that allow buildings to operate.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] It includes the electrotechnical, heating, ventilating, air conditioning, refrigeration and plumbing industries.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] To train as a building services engineer, the typical academic entry requirements include qualifications in mathematics and science, such as GCSEs (A-C) in England or Standard Grades (1-3) in Scotland.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Employers will often want a degree in a branch of engineering, such as building environment engineering, electrical engineering or mechanical engineering.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] To become a full member of CIBSE, and so also to be registered by the Engineering Council UK as a chartered engineer, engineers must also attain an Honours Degree and a master's degree in a relevant engineering subject.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] CIBSE publishes several guides to HVAC design relevant to the UK market, and also the Republic of Ireland, Australia, New Zealand and Hong Kong.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] These guides include various recommended design criteria and standards, some of which are cited within the UK building regulations, and therefore form a legislative requirement for major building services works.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Within the construction sector, it is the job of the building services engineer to design and oversee the installation and maintenance of the essential services such as gas, electricity, water, heating and lighting.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Building Services is part of a sector that has over 51,000 businesses and represents 2–3% of the GDP.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The Air Conditioning and Mechanical Contractors Association of Australia (AMCA), Australian Institute of Refrigeration, Air Conditioning and Heating (AIRAH), Australian Refrigeration Mechanical Association and CIBSE are responsible.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Asian architectural temperature-control have different priorities than European methods.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] For example, Asian heating traditionally focuses on maintaining temperatures of objects such as the floor or furnishings such as Kotatsu tables and directly warming people, as opposed to the Western focus, in modern periods, on designing air systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The Philippine Society of Ventilating, Air Conditioning and Refrigerating Engineers (PSVARE) along with Philippine Society of Mechanical Engineers (PSME) govern on the codes and standards for HVAC / MVAC (MVAC means "mechanical ventilation and air conditioning") in the Philippines.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] The Indian Society of Heating, Refrigerating and Air Conditioning Engineers (ISHRAE) was established to promote the HVAC industry in India.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] ISHRAE was founded at New Delhi in 1981 and a chapter was started in Bangalore in 1989.
[src:hvac-building-automation/heating-ventilation-and-air-conditioning] Between 1989 & 1993, ISHRAE chapters were formed in all major cities in India.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] The first HVAC controllers utilized pneumatic controls since engineers understood fluid control.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Thus, the properties of steam and air were used to control the flow of heated or cooled air via mechanically controlled logic.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] After the control of air flow and temperature was standardized, the use of electromechanical relays in ladder logic to switch dampers became standardized.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Eventually, the relays became electronic switches, as transistors eventually could handle greater current loads.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] By 1985, pneumatic controls could no longer compete with this new technology although pneumatic control systems (sometimes decades old) are still common in many older buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] By the year 2000, computerized controllers were common.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Today, some of these controllers can even be accessed by web browsers, which need no longer be in the same building as the HVAC equipment.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] This allows some economies of scale, as a single operations center can easily monitor multiple buildings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Prior to about the late 1960s, HVAC systems were controlled by pneumatics (using air pressure and tubes to move valves and dampers).
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Then, digital computerization began to replace those systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Central controllers and most terminal unit controllers are programmable, meaning the direct digital control (DDC) program code may be customized for the intended use.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] The program features include time schedules, set points, controllers, logic, timers, trend logs, and alarms.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] The unit controllers typically have analog and digital inputs that allow measurement of the variable (temperature, humidity, or pressure) and analog and digital outputs for control of the transport medium (hot/cold water and/or steam).
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Digital inputs are typically (dry) contacts from a control device, and analog inputs are typically a voltage or current measurement from a variable (temperature, humidity, velocity, or pressure) sensing device.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Digital outputs are typically relay contacts used to start and stop equipment, and analog outputs are typically voltage or current signals to control the movement of the medium (air/water/steam) control devices such as valves, dampers, and motors.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Groups of DDC controllers, networked or not, form a layer of systems themselves.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] This "subsystem" is vital to the performance and basic operation of the overall HVAC system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] The DDC system is the "brain" of the HVAC system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] It dictates the position of every damper and valve in a system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] It determines which fans, pumps, and chiller run and at what speed or capacity.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] With this configurable intelligence in this "brain", we are moving to the concept of building automation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] More complex HVAC systems can interface with a Building Automation System (BAS) to allow the building owners to have more control over the heating or cooling units.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] The building owner can monitor the system and respond to alarms generated by the system from local or remote locations.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] The system can be scheduled for occupancy or the configuration can be changed from the BAS.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Sometimes the BAS is directly controlling the HVAC components.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Depending on the BAS different interfaces can be used.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] Today, there are also dedicated gateways that connect advanced VRV / VRF and Split HVAC Systems with Home Automation and BMS (Building Management Systems) controllers for centralized control and monitoring, obviating the need to purchase more complex and expensive HVAC systems.
[src:hvac-building-automation/hvac-control-system] In addition, such gateway solutions are capable of providing remote control operation of all HVAC indoor units over the internet.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] It can use twisted pair (in a tree, line or star topology), powerline, RF, or IP links.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] On this network, the devices form distributed applications and tight interaction is possible.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] This is implemented via interworking models with standardised datapoint types and objects, modelling logical device channels.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] The KNX standard has been built on the OSI-based EIB communication stack extended with the physical layers, configuration modes and application experience of BatiBUS and EHS.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] KNX is not based on a specific hardware platform and a network can be controlled by anything from an 8-bit microcontroller to a PC, according to the demands of a particular building.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] The most common form of installation is over twisted pair medium.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] It is administered by the KNX Association cvba, a non-profit organisation governed by Belgian law which was formed in 1999.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] The KNX Association had 500 registered hardware and software vendor members from 45 nations as at 1 July 2021.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] It had partnership agreements with 100,000 installer companies in 172 countries and more than 500 registered training centres.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] This is a royalty-free open standard and thus access to the KNX specifications is unrestricted.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] KNX devices are commonly connected by a twisted pair bus and can be modified from a controller.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Classifying devices as either "sensor" or "actuator" is outdated and simplistic.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Many actuators include controller functionality, but also sensor functionality (for instance measuring operating hours, number of switch cycles, current, electrical power consumption, and more).
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Application software, together with system topology and commissioning software, is loaded onto the devices via a system interface component.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Installed systems can be accessed via LAN, point to point links, or phone networks for central or distributed control of the system via computers, tablets and touch screens, and smartphones.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Central to the KNX architecture concepts are **datapoints** (inputs, outputs, parameters, and diagnostic data) which represent process and control variables in the system.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] The standardised containers for these datapoints are **group objects** and **interface object properties**.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] The communication system offers a reduced instruction set to read and write datapoint values.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Datapoints have to conform to standardised **datapoint types**, themselves grouped into **functional blocks**.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] These functional blocks and datapoint types are related to applications fields, but some of them are of general use (such as date and time).
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Datapoints may be accessed through unicast or multicast mechanisms.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] The common kernel sits on top of the physical layers and the medium-specific data link layer and is shared by all the devices on the KNX Network.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] An installation has to be configured at the network topology level and at individual nodes or devices.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] The first level is a precondition or “bootstrap” phase, prior to the configuration of the distributed applications, i.e. binding and parameter setting.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Configuration may be achieved through a combination of local activity on the devices (such pushing a button), and active network management communication over the bus (peer-to-peer, or more centralized master-slave).
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Some modes require more active management over the bus, whereas some others are mainly oriented towards local configuration.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] KNX encompasses tools for project engineering tasks such as linking a series of individual devices into a functioning installation and integrating different media and configuration modes.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] This is embodied in an *Engineering Tool Software* (ETS) suite.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] A KNX installation always consists of a set of devices connected to the bus or network.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Device models vary according to node roles, capabilities, management features and configuration modes, and are all laid down in the **profiles**.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] There are also general-purpose device models, such as for bus coupling units (BCUs) or bus interface modules (BIMs).
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Devices may be identified and subsequently accessed throughout the network either by their individual address, or by their unique serial number, depending on the configuration mode.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] (Unique serial numbers are allocated by the KNX Association Certification Department.) Devices can also disclose both a manufacturer specific reference and functional (manufacturer independent) information when queried.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] A KNX wired network can be formed with tree, line and star topologies, which can be mixed as needed; ring topologies are *not* supported.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] A tree topology is recommended for a large installation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] KNX can link up to 57,375 devices using 16-bit addresses.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Coupling units allow address filtering which helps to improve performance given the limited bus signal speed.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] An installation based on KNXnet/IP allows the integration of KNX sub networks via IP as the KNX address structure is similar to an IP address.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] The TP1 twisted pair bus (inherited from EIB) provides asynchronous, character oriented data transfer and half-duplex bidirectional differential signaling with a signaling speed of 9600 bit/s.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Every bus user has equal data transmission rights and data is exchanged directly (peer-to-peer) between bus users.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] SELV power is distributed via the same pair for low-power devices.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] A deprecated specification, TP0, running at a slower signalling speed of 4800 bit/s, has been retained from the BatiBUS standard but KNX products cannot exchange information with BatiBUS devices.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] PL 110 power-line transmission is delivered using spread frequency shift keying signalling with asynchronous transmission of data packets and half duplex bi-directional communication.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] It uses the central frequency 110 kHz (CENELEC B-band) and has a data rate of 1200 bit/s.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] KNX Powerline is aimed at smart white goods, but the take-up has been low.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] An alternative variant, PL 132, has a carrier frequency centred on 132.5 kHz (CENELEC C-band).
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] RF enables communication in the 868.3 MHz band for using frequency shift keying with Manchester data encoding.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] KNXnet/IP port 3671 has integration solutions for IP-enabled media like Ethernet (IEEE 802.2), Bluetooth, WiFi/Wireless LAN (IEEE 802.11), FireWire (IEEE 1394) etc.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] KNX Telegrams can be signed or encrypted thanks to the extension of the protocol that was developed starting in 2013, KNX Data Secure for securing telegrams on the traditional KNX media TP and RF and KNX IP Secure for securing KNX telegrams tunnelled via IP.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] KNX Data Secure became an EN standard (EN 50090-3-4) in 2018, KNX IP Secure an ISO standard (ISO 22510) in 2019.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] Any product labeled with the KNX trademark must be certified to conform with the standards (and thus interoperable with other devices) by accredited third party test labs.
[src:hvac-building-automation/knx-standard] All products bearing the KNX logo are programmed through a common interface using the vendor-independent ETS software.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] The technology had its origins with chip designs, power lines, twisted pairs, signaling technology, routers, network management software, and other products from Echelon Corporation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] In 1999 the communications protocol (then known as LonTalk) was submitted to ANSI and accepted as a standard for control networking (**ANSI/CEA-709.1-B**).
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] Echelon's power line and twisted pair signaling technology were also submitted to ANSI for standardization and acceptance.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] The protocol is also one of several data link/physical layers of the BACnet ASHRAE/ANSI standard for building automation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] In 2008, ISO and IEC granted the communications protocol, twisted pair signaling technology, power line signaling technology, and Internet Protocol (IP) compatibility standard numbers ISO/IEC 14908-1, -2, -3, and -4.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] By 2010, approximately 90 million devices were installed with LonWorks technology.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] Manufacturers in a variety of industries including building, home, street lighting, transportation, utility, and industrial automation have adopted the platform as the basis for their product and service offerings.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] Two physical-layer signaling technologies, twisted pair *free topology* and power-line carrier, are typically included in each of the standards created around the LonWorks technology.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] The two-wire layer operates at 78 kbit/s using differential Manchester encoding, while the power line achieves either 5.4 or 3.6 kbit/s, depending on frequency.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] Additionally, the LonWorks platform uses an affiliated IP tunneling standard—ISO/IEC 14908-4 (ANSI/CEA-852)—in use by a number of manufacturers to connect the devices on previously deployed and new LonWorks platform-based networks to IP-aware applications or remote network-management tools.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] Many LonWorks platform-based control applications are being implemented with some sort of IP integration, either at the UI/application level or in the controls infrastructure.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] This is accomplished with Web services or IP-routing products available in the market.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] An Echelon Corporation-designed IC consisting of several 8-bit processors, the *Neuron chip* was initially the only way to implement a LonTalk protocol node and is used in the large majority of LonWorks platform-based hardware.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] Since 1999, the protocol has been available for general-purpose processors: A port of the ANSI/CEA-709.1 standard to IP-based or 32-bit chips.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] As of 14 September, 2018, Echelon Corporation was acquired by Adesto Technologies Corporation.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] Adesto was then acquired by Dialog Semiconductor who were then acquired by Renesas Electronics.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] As of 2024, Renesas continues to offer LonWorks (and BACnet) products.
[src:hvac-building-automation/lonworks] One of the keys to the interoperability of the system is the standardisation of the variables used to describe physical things to LonWorks.
